    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>Types of Feline Cancer</h2>
      <p>Cancer in cats covers a wide range of diseases — from highly treatable to rapidly progressive. The most common types include lymphoma (affecting the lymphatic system), mammary (breast) tumours, squamous cell carcinoma, mast cell tumours, and soft tissue sarcomas.</p>
      <p>Murphy had mammary cancer. She also had a brief period of hyperthyroidism before the cancer diagnosis — a reminder that senior cats rarely present with just one condition, and each interacts with the others.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>Mammary cancer note:</strong> Approximately 85% of mammary tumours in cats are malignant, compared to about 50% in dogs. Early detection and spaying before the first heat cycle are the best prevention. For unspayed cats, any lump near the mammary chain warrants prompt veterinary attention — not a wait-and-see approach.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="signs" class="content-section">
      <h2>Signs to Watch For</h2>
      <p>Many of the signs of cancer in cats overlap with other conditions — which is part of why diagnosis can be delayed. General signs to bring to your vet promptly:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Unexplained weight loss, especially rapid</li>
        <li>Loss of appetite that doesn't respond to anti-nausea treatment</li>
        <li>Lumps or swellings anywhere on the body — have these assessed, don't assume benign</li>
        <li>Sores that don't heal</li>
        <li>Difficulty eating, swallowing, or breathing</li>
        <li>Changes in bathroom habits — straining, blood in urine or stool</li>
        <li>Sudden lethargy, hiding, or marked behaviour change</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>Don't wait on lumps.</strong> A lump that has been there for a while and "seems stable" can still be malignant. The only way to know is cytology or biopsy. Ask for it.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="diagnosis" class="content-section">
      <h2>Diagnosis and Staging</h2>
      <p>Diagnosing cancer in cats typically involves some combination of physical examination, bloodwork, imaging (X-ray, ultrasound), fine needle aspirate (FNA) cytology, and biopsy. FNA is minimally invasive and gives a quick initial answer — though it doesn't always provide enough information, in which case a biopsy gives more definitive results.</p>
      <p>Staging — understanding how far the cancer has spread — typically involves chest X-rays to check for lung metastasis and abdominal ultrasound to assess lymph nodes and organs. Staging affects both prognosis and the appropriateness of aggressive treatment.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>Ask specifically:</strong> "What staging has been done, and what does it tell us about whether treatment is likely to be curative or palliative?" This distinction matters enormously for making decisions.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="treatment" class="content-section">
      <h2>Treatment Options</h2>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Surgery</div>
          <div class="med-desc">For solid tumours, surgical removal is often the first treatment. Margins matter — clean margins (no cancer cells at the edges) indicate a better chance of full removal. Ask specifically about margin status after any tumour removal.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Chemotherapy</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Used for lymphoma and other systemic cancers, and sometimes as an adjunct after surgery for solid tumours. Cats generally tolerate chemotherapy better than humans — hair loss is not typical in cats. Murphy went through chemotherapy; it didn't help her. That outcome is real, and so is the fact that it does help many cats significantly.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Radiation therapy</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Used for certain tumour types, particularly those not fully removable by surgery. Requires referral to a specialist facility. Not available everywhere in North America — ask your vet about referral options if it's relevant to your cat's diagnosis.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Palliative / comfort care</div>
          <div class="med-desc">When curative treatment is not possible or has stopped working, palliative care focuses on managing pain, maintaining appetite, and maximising quality of daily life. This is a legitimate and loving treatment choice — not giving up.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="stopping" class="content-section">
      <h2>When Treatment Stops Working — or When to Stop</h2>
      <p>Murphy's vet recommended against more chemotherapy when it became clear it wasn't helping. That recommendation — stopping aggressive treatment — is one of the hardest conversations to have, and one of the most important.</p>
      <p>There is a significant difference between a vet who says "there's nothing more we can do" when there are actually more options, and a vet who says "more treatment is likely to cause more suffering than benefit." Learning to distinguish between those two situations is hard.</p>

      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Questions to ask when a vet recommends stopping treatment:</strong>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
          <li>What specifically has led you to this recommendation?</li>
          <li>Is there a specialist — a veterinary oncologist — whose opinion we should seek?</li>
          <li>If we continue treatment, what is the realistic best case?</li>
          <li>What does comfort-focused care look like from here?</li>
          <li>How will we know when quality of life has declined to the point where we should consider euthanasia?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <p>Seeking a second opinion from a veterinary oncologist is always reasonable when you're facing a decision to stop treatment. This is not distrust of your vet — it is appropriate due diligence for a major decision. In the US and Canada, veterinary oncologists are available at most specialist referral centres and veterinary schools.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Is this a primary tumour or has it spread? What staging has been done?</li>
        <li>Are the surgical margins clean? What does that mean for recurrence risk?</li>
        <li>Is the goal of treatment curative or palliative? Are we clear on that?</li>
        <li>What is the expected quality of life during treatment?</li>
        <li>Should we consult a veterinary oncologist?</li>
        <li>If we don't pursue aggressive treatment, what does comfort care look like?</li>
        <li>How will we assess quality of life as this progresses?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

